english:
  title: Preface to Poems Presented to Magistrate Song Upon His Appointment to Hanyang
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas! Loyalty as a minister and filial piety as a son—these two are the greatest principles of human conduct and the foundation of an upright life. Yet the positions we occupy differ, and time and circumstance often run contrary, never aligning as we wish. Thus loyalty and filial piety cannot always both be fulfilled, and those who serve as minister and son may harbor some regret.

    Magistrate Song of Hanyang fulfilled his filial duty toward his parents with utmost care. He first dwelt in Boseong of Jeolla Province, but when sea pirates raided deeply and wrought havoc, he bore his parents upon his shoulders and fled through wild grasslands, fearing they might not escape. He journeyed far to Gwajeon in Yanggwang Province, rented fields and a dwelling, and labored with his servants in agriculture to provide his parents with sustenance. The people of the region, moved by his filial devotion, sent many gifts. When his father passed, from the initial mourning through the funeral rites and sacrifices, he observed all propriety, his grief moving the entire neighborhood. He honored his mother's passing with the same devotion.

    At this time, the state was appointing officials through the established system, placing particular emphasis on magistrates. An order was sent to the provincial administration to recommend worthy candidates, and Song's name rose to the lips of all. They spoke with one voice: "Benevolent and incorruptible, fit to govern the people." Thus, ignoring his status as a mourner, he was appointed Vice Prefect of Jeongseon with the rank of Feng-shan Daifu. Song submitted a memorial requesting exemption, saying: "My parents' graves lie distant, and I cannot personally perform the rites at the new and full moons. I humbly request that I be permitted to complete my mourning period." His words were deeply moving.

    The court deliberated: "The heart of a filial son cannot be denied, yet magistrates of such character are rare. Since Hanyang lies mere tens of li from Gwajeon, he may perform his duties by day and visit the graves for his monthly rites in the intervals between judgments. Thus both purposes may be served." Accordingly, he was appointed Magistrate of Hanyang, though his rank was lowered to Tongzhi Lang due to administrative constraint. The summons came urgently, and reluctantly he departed for his post.

    Alas! In the pursuit of advancement, men typically calculate even a single step up the ladder. Yet Song, for the sake of his parents, has forsaken the higher position for the lower. This speaks to his wisdom and virtue—filial piety is already perfected, and surely loyalty shall now flourish in this new service. The gentlemen, admiring Song's noble resolve, have all composed verses to present to him as a token of friendship. Being his fellow countryman, I too dare count myself fortunate, and thus I have written this preface.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'new and full moons' (朔望) refer to the first and fifteenth days of the lunar month, when filial descendants traditionally performed sacrifices at ancestral graves.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'one resource half-rank' (一資半級) refers to the customary ambition of officials to gain even small increments of rank and privilege.
  - key: ''
    value: Hanyang (modern Seoul) and Gwajeon (modern Gwacheon) are indeed only about 20-30 kilometers apart, making the court's compromise both practical and compassionate.
